This MS. has a singular history. Presented to Henry VIII. by two Greek Bishops who are said to have brought it from Philippi, it was given by Elizabeth to Sir John Fortescue‚ by whom it was subsequently placed in the collection of Sir R. Cotton. Lent by Sir Richard to Lord Arundel in 1630, it fell into other hands, but was ultimately secured again for the Cotton¹ Library by Sir John Cotton. In 1700 the Library became national pro- perty, and the safety of the MS. might have seemed thenceforth secured. Unhappily it was removed with the rest of the collection to Ashburnham House, and reduced to charred fragments by the fire which attacked the treasures of that establishment Oct. 23, 1731. Dr H. Owen writingin 1778 speaks of the fragments as hopelessly lost; but the Cottonian catalogue of 1802 mentions 18 of them as still preserved at the British Museum, to which the Cotton library had meanwhile been transferred; and further search has largely added to this number. The scraps were collected with scrupulous care in 1847-81. Three or four other fragments have been discovered at the Bristol Baptist College, to which they were hequeathed by Dr A. Gifford, a London Baptist minister who had been officially con· nected with the department of MSS. at the British Museum.
